==English==
===Etymology===
First attested circa [[w:1540|1540]], from {{L.}} [[truculentus]], "[[fierce]], [[savage]]," from [[trux]], genitive of [[trucis]], "[[fierce]], [[wild]]."

===Pronunciation===
*{{AHD|\trŭkyə-lənt\}}

===Adjective===
'''truculent'''

# [[fierce]]; [[savage]]; [[ferocious]]; [[barbarous]]
#:''The '''truculent''' inhabitants of Scythia.''
# [[cruel]]; [[destructive]]; [[ruthless]].
# [[defiant]]; [[uncompromising]].

===Examples===
William Golding:

:'''''Truculently''' they squared up to each other but kept just out of fighting distance?''
:—The Lord of the Flies, chapter 11

